(a) Consider the following differential equation for $y=y(x)$: $xy''-(2x+1)y'+(x+1)y=0$ for $x>0$. Given that $y_{1}(x)=e^{x}$ is one solution of (1), find the general solution of (1). [8]
(b) Hence, find the general solution of the following differential equation for $y=y(x)$: $xy''-(2x+1)y'+(x+1)y=x^{2}$, $x>0$. [8]
(c) The Fourier series for $f(x)=x^{7}+2x^{3}$ on $[-1,1]$ is given by a function $g(x)$. State whether each of the following statements are true or false, justifying your answer in each case. You do not need to derive $g(x)$.
(i) $g(0)=0$;
(ii) $g(1)=3$;
(iii) $g(-1)=g(1)$;
(iv) $g(x)$ contains terms in $\cos(n\pi x)$, $n\in\mathbb{N}$. [9]

(a) Consider $x^{2}y''-2xy'-4y=0, x>0$. Given $y_{1}(x)=x^{-1}$ is a solution, find the general solution. [9]
(b) Find the general solution for $x^{2}y''-2xy'-4y=x^{5}, x>0$. [8]
(c) Match four ODEs (A-D) with given power series solutions (i-iv) without solving, justifying each case.
(A) $y''-xy'+2y=\cos(x)$;
(B) $(x+1)y''-x^{2}y'+3y=0$;
(C) $y'-e^{x}y=0$;
(D) $3xy''+(2-x)y'-y=0$.
Solutions: (i) $y(x)=\alpha_{1}(1-\frac{3}{2}x^{2}+...)+\alpha_{2}(x-\frac{x^{3}}{2}+...)$; (ii) $y(x)=\alpha_{1}(x^{\frac{1}{3}}+...)+\alpha_{2}(1+...)$; (iii) $y(x)=\alpha_{1}(1-x^{2})+\alpha_{2}(x-\frac{x^{3}}{6}-...)+(\frac{x^{2}}{2}-...)$; (iv) $y(x)=\alpha_{1}(1+x+x^{2}+...)$. [8]
